issue.title: [JOSS Review] Clarify Requirements for Controls and Trajectory Planning
issue.body:
I was unable to execute the controls and trajectory planning examples shown in documentation. There is a helpful note clarifying CUDA requirements in the [Simulation](https://manipulapy.readthedocs.io/en/latest/user_guide/Simulation.html) section of the documentation. This should also be shown for all sections which require CUDA or GPU support.

As described in #17, it would be helpful to summarize what features are CPU-only compatible in documentation, and also in the paper.

I also see failures executing vision code examples. On importing `cv2` in `ManipulaPy.vision`, the following `ImportError` is raised. This does not need to be fixed, but requirements should be clarified. 

```
ImportError: libGL.so.1: cannot open shared object file: No such file or directory
```

---

This issue is part of a [JOSS Review](https://github.com/openjournals/joss-reviews/issues/8490).

issue.title: [Feedback] Network Console will be removed in Edge 143
issue.body:
Starting with Edge 143, the Network Console tool will be removed from Edge DevTools with no replacement. As our team shifts focus toward delivering more stable features and improving alignment with Chrome, we no longer have the capacity to maintain this tool. We recommend using the REST Client extension for VS Code for API development and testing.

If this feature is important to your workflow, we encourage you to share your feedback. Strong interest could help motivate bringing it to Chromium in the future.

comment.body:
I'll be blunt: this is a baffling and profoundly out-of-touch decision.
To suggest a VS Code extension as a replacement for the Network Console is to fundamentally misunderstand the tool's purpose and our workflow. It's not just a "recommendation," it's a dismissal of the very context-sensitive, in-the-moment debugging that made the tool essential.
Let's call this what it is:
It's a regression, not an improvement. You are actively making your browser a worse tool for developers. The argument about "shifting focus to stable features" is a hollow excuse for removing a feature that was not only stable but was a key differentiator.
It's a surrender of innovation. You had a feature that made developers seriously consider, and even choose, Edge over Chrome. It was a tangible advantage. Now, you are voluntarily throwing that advantage away to become a less-capable clone. Why would we choose a browser that actively removes its best features?
It demonstrates a disconnect from your users. This decision feels like it was made in a vacuum by people who don't actually use the DevTools for complex, day-to-day debugging. If you did, you would know that breaking the browser-context loop is a dealbreaker.
This isn't about "strong interest." We are telling you now: you are removing a critical piece of our toolkit and making our jobs harder for what appears to be your own convenience.
This is how you lose the goodwill of the developer community you've worked so hard to win back. Reverse this decision.

feat: Elevate topic content experience with multiple enhancements

This commit introduces several new features to significantly enhance the user experience of the Belize travel map, addressing the goal of elevating the "wow factor".

The key enhancements include:

- **Dynamic Constellation Background:** A new `constellations.js` file creates a subtle, animated starfield background. When a location is selected, it draws "constellation" lines connecting it to other related points of interest, reinforcing the "elemental journey" theme.

- **Interactive Filtering:** Users can now filter locations by category (All, Ruins, Nature, Marine) using a new set of filter buttons at the top of the page. This allows for a more focused exploration of the map.

- **Keyboard Navigation:** The map now supports keyboard navigation. Users can cycle through the visible locations using the left and right arrow keys, providing a more fluid browsing experience.

- **Enriched Content Panel:**
    - A new "Atmosphere" section has been added to each location, providing a poetic, thematic description to enhance the narrative.
    - A subtle parallax effect has been added to the panel image, making it feel more dynamic as the user scrolls the content.

- **Data Enrichment:** The location data has been updated with `type_category` for filtering and the new `atmosphere` text.

These changes are integrated cleanly into the existing application structure, building upon the original design philosophy to create a more immersive, interactive, and informative journey.

issue.title: feat(proto): implement comprehensive Protocol Buffer reorganization infrastructure
issue.body:
This PR implements the complete infrastructure for reorganizing 1,632+ Protocol Buffer files from the scattered `pkg/*/proto/` structure to an organized `proto/gcommon/v1/` hierarchy following Buf best practices and industry standards.

## Problem Statement

The repository currently has Protocol Buffer files scattered across multiple inconsistent directory patterns:
- `pkg/config_1/proto/`, `pkg/config_2/proto/`, `pkg/config_api/proto/` (fragmented config domain)
- `pkg/metrics_1/proto/`, `pkg/metrics_2/proto/` (versioning inconsistencies)
- Mixed naming conventions and package structures
- Complex import paths with `pkg/` prefixes making navigation difficult
- No centralized proto organization following industry best practices

## Solution Overview

Implements a comprehensive 12-phase migration system that safely reorganizes all proto files into a clean, scalable structure:

**Target Architecture:**
```
proto/gcommon/v1/
├── common/{types,messages,enums,services}/     # Common utilities (auth, health, logs)
├── config/{api,v1,v2,services}/               # Unified configuration domain  
├── database/{config,services,types,schema}/   # Database and caching
├── media/{types,metadata,services,processing}/ # Media processing
├── metrics/{v1,v2,services,types}/            # Metrics and monitoring
├── organization/{api,config,services,types}/  # Organization management
├── queue/{api,config,services,types}/         # Queue and messaging
└── web/{api,config,events,services}/          # Web services and events
```

## Key Features

### 🤖 Complete Automation
- **Master migration script** (`scripts/master-migration.sh`) orchestrates the entire 12-phase process
- **Intelligent file categorization** automatically places files in appropriate subdirectories
- **Import path updates** throughout all proto files with dependency resolution
- **Package name standardization** to `gcommon.v1.{domain}.{category}` format
- **Buf managed mode** configuration for consistent Go code generation

### 🛡️ Safety & Reliability
- **Comprehensive backup system** (git branches + filesystem snapshots)
- **Dry-run mode** for safe testing before actual execution
- **Multi-level validation** at each migration phase
- **Rollback procedures** for quick recovery if issues arise
- **Emergency stop and recovery tools** with interactive assistance

### 🧪 Testing & Validation
- **Pre-migration testing** validates current state and dependencies
- **Progressive testing** ensures each domain migrates correctly
- **Import resolution testing** verifies all paths resolve properly
- **Performance testing** compares build times before/after
- **Final verification** runs comprehensive system checks

### 📊 Migration Intelligence
- **Domain mapping strategy** consolidates scattered directories (config_1, config_2 → config)
- **Dependency analysis** determines optimal migration order
- **File categorization logic** based on naming patterns and content analysis
- **Cross-domain import resolution** maintains all existing relationships

## Usage Examples

```bash
# Preview the complete migration plan
./scripts/master-migration.sh --dry-run

# Execute full migration with backups and validation
./scripts/master-migration.sh

# Migrate specific domains for testing
./scripts/master-migration.sh --domain common

# Emergency rollback if needed
./scripts/orchestrate-migration.sh rollback
```

## Benefits

### Immediate
- **Organized structure** following Buf best practices and industry standards
- **Consistent naming** eliminates confusion from scattered directories
- **Better tooling support** with improved IDE navigation and code completion
- **Automated validation** prevents proto syntax and import issues

### Long-term
- **Scalable architecture** makes adding new domains and services straightforward
- **Reduced complexity** in development workflows and build systems
- **Improved collaboration** with clear domain boundaries and ownership
- **Future-proof design** aligns with Protocol Buffer ecosystem evolution

## Migration Scope

- **1,632+ proto files** across 8 core domains
- **Unified configuration** consolidates config_1, config_2, config_api into single domain
- **Metrics standardization** merges metrics_1, metrics_2 with proper versioning
- **Common domain** consolidates auth, health, log, notification utilities
- **Buf managed mode** ensures consistent Go package generation paths

## Safety Measures

The implementation includes extensive safety features:
- Git backup branches with timestamps for complete state restoration
- Filesystem backups for additional protection
- Comprehensive validation at each step with detailed error reporting
- Emergency procedures and interactive recovery assistance
- Rollback testing to ensure restoration procedures work correctly

This infrastructure transforms the repository from a scattered collection of proto files into a well-organized, maintainable, and scalable Protocol Buffer ecosystem ready for long-term growth and development.

pull_request.title: feat(code): allow nodes to run in sync-only mode without participating in consensus
pull_request.body:
Closes: #XXX
Adds new Sync-Only mode for Full Nodes

Behavior:

- Subscribes only to sync network topics
- Downloads and validates blocks
- Does not process consensus messages (proposals, votes, certificates)
- Does not participate in voting or proposal validation

Use Cases: 
- Block explorers, read-only applications, archival nodes
- Validators that are far behind
   - The UX is not great: starts with `consensus.enable=false`, when close to the tip, the validator needs to be manually restarted with updated config: `consensus.enable=true`
   - For this use case we should have config reload or even better rejoining consensus when getting close to the tip

---

pull_request.title: chore(utils): Remove hash algorithm from certificate leaf computation
pull_request.body:
This PR removes the hash algorithm specified on the CSC from the leaf computation used in the certificate registry merkle tree. 

The reason for this change is that the hash algorithm specified on the CSC is not guaranteed to be the one used for signing the DSC, but only for whatever signed the CSC itself (either self-signing or signed by another certificate). This can only be determined fully accurately from the DSC signature algorithm information, and therefore is harder to determine beforehand with complete certainty.

issue.title: feat(cli): add --link flag to link configs without installs (issue #29)
issue.body:
# feat(cli): add --link flag to link configs without installs (issue #29) ## Summary This PR implements a new `--link` CLI flag that enables "link-only" operations as requested in issue #29. When used, the flag creates or updates symlinks for configuration files without running install commands, exporting/importing defaults, or persisting state changes. **Key Features:** - **Link-only execution**: Only processes `link` sections from components, skipping `install` commands - **Postlink hook support**: Runs postlink hooks when present and linking succeeds - **Profile & fuzzy search support**: Works with the same profile selection and fuzzy search as regular runs - **No state persistence**: Intentionally bypasses profile saving and component state updates - **Progress & verbose modes**: Supports both `--verbose` and quiet (progress) execution modes **Files Changed:** - `cmd/dot/main.go`: Added CLI flag, execution path, and state persistence guard - `internal/component/component.go`: Added `LinkComponents` and `LinkComponentsWithProgress` methods - `cmd/dot/main_test.go` & `internal/component/component_test.go`: Added test coverage - `README.md`: Updated with usage examples and behavior description ## Review & Testing Checklist for Human - [ ] **End-to-end testing**: Run `dot --link`, `dot --link [profile]`, and `dot --link [fuzzy]` to verify basic functionality works as expected - [ ] **State isolation**: Verify that link-only operations don't modify `~/.dot/state.json` or persist profile changes (key behavioral difference) - [ ] **Postlink hook execution**: Test components with postlink hooks to ensure they run correctly and handle failures appropriately - [ ] **Error handling**: Test edge cases like components with no links, missing files, permission errors, and failed postlink hooks - [ ] **CLI integration**: Verify the flag works correctly with other flags like `--dry-run`, `--verbose`, and doesn't conflict with existing operations **Recommended Test Plan:** 1. Create a test component with both `install` and `link` sections plus a postlink hook 2. Run `dot --link [component]` and verify only linking occurs (no installs, no state changes) 3. Test with existing components like `neovim` to ensure expected output: `✔︎ *.cli.neovim linked` --- ### Diagram ```mermaid %%{ init : { "theme" : "default" }}%% graph TD CLI["cmd/dot/main.go
CLI Entry Point"]:::major-edit ComponentMgr["internal/component/component.go
Component Manager"]:::major-edit CLITest["cmd/dot/main_test.go
CLI Flag Tests"]:::minor-edit ComponentTest["internal/component/component_test.go
Link Component Tests"]:::minor-edit README["README.md
Documentation"]:::minor-edit LinkMgr["internal/link/link.go
Link Manager"]:::context StateMgr["internal/state/state.go
State Manager"]:::context ExecMgr["internal/exec/exec.go
Exec Manager"]:::context CLI --> ComponentMgr ComponentMgr --> LinkMgr ComponentMgr --> StateMgr ComponentMgr --> ExecMgr CLI -.-> CLITest ComponentMgr -.-> ComponentTest subgraph Legend L1[Major Edit]:::major-edit L2[Minor Edit]:::minor-edit L3[Context/No Edit]:::context end classDef major-edit fill:#90EE90 classDef minor-edit fill:#87CEEB classDef context fill:#FFFFFF ``` ### Notes - **Link to Devin run**: https://app.devin.ai/sessions/4e6e13fa143142f898eecabb545ace40 - **Requested by**: @pablopunk - **Testing limitation**: Unable to run tests locally due to go not being available on the development VM - relying on CI for validation - **Behavioral design choice**: Link-only mode intentionally skips state persistence to avoid side effects, but still runs postlink hooks which may have their own side effects - **CLI complexity**: The main execution path now has multiple conditional branches that should be carefully tested to ensure correct behavior in all scenarios

pull_request.title: chore: Add Claude Code GitHub Workflow
pull_request.body:
## 🤖 Installing Claude Code GitHub App

This PR adds a GitHub Actions workflow that enables Claude Code integration in our repository.

### What is Claude Code?

[Claude Code](https://claude.ai/code) is an AI coding agent that can help with:
- Bug fixes and improvements  
- Documentation updates
- Implementing new features
- Code reviews and suggestions
- Writing tests
- And more!

### How it works

Once this PR is merged, we'll be able to interact with Claude by mentioning @claude in a pull request or issue comment.
Once the workflow is triggered, Claude will analyze the comment and surrounding context, and execute on the request in a GitHub action.

### Important Notes

- **This workflow won't take effect until this PR is merged**
- **@claude mentions won't work until after the merge is complete**
- The workflow runs automatically whenever Claude is mentioned in PR or issue comments
- Claude gets access to the entire PR or issue context including files, diffs, and previous comments

### Security

- Our Anthropic API key is securely stored as a GitHub Actions secret
- Only users with write access to the repository can trigger the workflow
- All Claude runs are stored in the GitHub Actions run history
- Claude's default tools are limited to reading/writing files and interacting with our repo by creating comments, branches, and commits.
- We can add more allowed tools by adding them to the workflow file like:

```
allowed_tools: Bash(npm install),Bash(npm run build),Bash(npm run lint),Bash(npm run test)
```

There's more information in the [Claude Code action repo](https://github.com/anthropics/claude-code-action).

After merging this PR, let's try mentioning @claude in a comment on any PR to get started!

pull_request.title: app_rpt.c: Warn when using pipe delimiter in dialplan instead of comma.
pull_request.body:
The pipe (`|`) delimiter was previously used in OLD Asterisk. The current delimiter is the comma (`,`). We currently support either, but the plan is to stop supporting the pipe at sometime in the future.

This change warns users that there is a pipe in their dialplan (in extensions.conf) and reminds them to change it.

UpgradeNote: Users should update calls to Rpt to use the comma delimiter to prevent future errors.
